After a deflating defeat at the Chinnaswamy four days ago, David Warner reckoned Delhi Capitals needed to take a 'hard look' at themselves. The franchise will hope the break would've brought the much-needed mental rejuvenation after five successive losses. Only one team in the history of the IPL has ever recovered from such an ignominious start to go all the way. For DC, going all the way is a distant dream; for now, they need the first points on the board.   
   
And that pursuit will be down to how well their batting gets together and puts on a cohesive effort. DC have felt the absence of Rishabh Pant, but the batting unit, even without him, should've done better in a couple of the losses they suffered. By his own admission, Warner has struggled for timing even though he has been among the runs. That, combined with Prithvi Shaw's poor start to the season, has meant DC have had stuttered starts in all games and have struggled to play catch up from there. Any chance of turning their dreadful form and fortunes around rests with a top-order resurrection.   
   
KKR's plight this season is slightly less traumatic. The four points on the board have come from two pieces rabbit-out-of-the-hat kind of individual brilliance - first from Shardul Thakur and then Rinku Singh. Outside of that, they've been rather ordinary as a collective, even losing the game where they had a Venkatesh Iyer century. Four teams above them are only two points ahead and KKR have the advantage of a better Net Run Rate than all of them. The route to making the ascent is there for Nitish Rana's side, if they can put in a collective effort, as opposed to rely on individual brilliance.
